---
import MarketingLayout from '../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro';
---

<MarketingLayout
	title="A Programming Language With Bite"
	description="Mog is a strictly typed programming language with a bytecode VM, REPL, native packages, and editor tooling. Start with the official docs."
>
	<section class="hero-grid">
		<div class="hero-copy">
			<span class="eyebrow">Official Website + Docs</span>
			<h1>Strict by default. Small rules. Real tooling.</h1>
			<p>
				Mog is a bytecode-compiled programming language implemented in C++ with a VM, compiler,
				REPL, native package system, and editor tooling in the same repository. The design goal is
				clarity without softness.
			</p>
			<div class="hero-actions">
				<a class="primary" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Read the Quickstart</a>
				<a class="secondary" href="/docs/reference/syntax-rules/">Browse the Reference</a>
			</div>
			<div class="hero-metrics">
				<div class="metric-card">
					<strong>Typed</strong>
					<span>Explicit signatures, local inference, and strict defaults.</span>
				</div>
				<div class="metric-card">
					<strong>Compiled</strong>
					<span>Bytecode compiler and stack-based virtual machine.</span>
				</div>
				<div class="metric-card">
					<strong>Tooled</strong>
					<span>REPL, diagnostics flags, VS Code extension, and LSP.</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="code-panel" aria-label="Mog code sample">
			<div class="code-panel__top">
				<div class="code-dots" aria-hidden="true"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
				<span>flappy_core.mog</span>
			</div>
			<pre><code><span class="kw">fn</span> <span class="fn">makeAdder</span>(base <span class="type">i32</span>) <span class="type">fn(i32) i32</span> &#123;
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">fn</span>(delta <span class="type">i32</span>) =&gt; base + delta
&#125;

<span class="kw">type</span> <span class="type">Bird</span> struct &#123;
  velocity <span class="type">f64</span>

  <span class="kw">fn</span> <span class="fn">jump</span>() &#123;
    this.velocity = -280.0
  &#125;
&#125;

<span class="kw">const</span> window = @import(<span class="str">"window"</span>)
<span class="kw">var</span> addTen = makeAdder(10)
print(addTen(32))</code></pre>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="feature-band">
		<article class="feature-card">
			<span class="eyebrow">Language Shape</span>
			<h3>Readable syntax without ceremonial noise</h3>
			<p>
				No semicolons in normal statement syntax, explicit continuation rules, and type signatures
				where they matter. Mog is compact without becoming vague.
			</p>
		</article>
		<article class="feature-card">
			<span class="eyebrow">Runtime</span>
			<h3>Compiler and VM in the same repo</h3>
			<p>
				The current implementation includes a Pratt parser, HIR lowering, optimization passes,
				bytecode emission, stack traces, and frontend timing diagnostics.
			</p>
		</article>
		<article class="feature-card">
			<span class="eyebrow">Packages + Tooling</span>
			<h3>Imports, native packages, and editor support</h3>
			<p>
				Use `@import(...)` for modules and native packages, build with `mog.toml`, and work with
				VS Code language support plus an in-repo LSP implementation.
			</p>
		</article>
	</section>

	<section class="content-section">
		<div class="section-header">
			<span class="eyebrow">What Ships In V1</span>
			<h2>A landing page for the pitch, and docs that stay close to the code.</h2>
			<p>
				The public site is one Astro app. The landing page handles positioning and narrative. The
				docs run on Starlight so you get search, navigation, Markdown authoring, and static output
				without building a documentation framework from nothing.
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="stack-grid">
			<article class="stack-card">
				<h3>Why this approach</h3>
				<p>
					Most documentation sites use a framework or platform instead of custom-building docs UI.
					For Mog, Astro + Starlight gives you a modern docs experience while leaving the landing
					page fully customizable.
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>Static output suitable for Vercel, Netlify, or any CDN</li>
					<li>In-repo Markdown and MDX content with searchable builds</li>
					<li>Design control without recreating docs navigation from scratch</li>
				</ul>
			</article>
			<article class="stack-card">
				<h3>What the stack looks like</h3>
				<p>
					The repo now acts as a real monorepo: the language runtime stays in C++ and the website
					lives under <code>apps/site</code>.
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li><code>npm</code> workspaces at the repo root</li>
					<li><code>Astro</code> for custom pages and static delivery</li>
					<li><code>Starlight</code> for docs, sidebar, search, and content collections</li>
				</ul>
			</article>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-section">
		<div class="section-header">
			<span class="eyebrow">Official Docs</span>
			<h2>Docs organized around getting productive fast, then understanding the language deeply.</h2>
			<p>
				The docs are intentionally split between workflow pages and durable reference pages so the
				site does not collapse into a giant README.
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="docs-grid">
			<article class="docs-card">
				<h3>Getting Started</h3>
				<p>Build the interpreter, run your first file, and understand the current project shape.</p>
			</article>
			<article class="docs-card">
				<h3>Language Guides</h3>
				<p>Learn bindings, control flow, collections, closures, types, imports, and type-checking rules.</p>
			</article>
			<article class="docs-card">
				<h3>Tooling</h3>
				<p>Use the REPL, diagnostics flags, VS Code extension, and the language server.</p>
			</article>
			<article class="docs-card">
				<h3>Reference</h3>
				<p>Check syntax rules, built-in functions, and current compiler/runtime flags quickly.</p>
			</article>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-section">
		<div class="section-header">
			<span class="eyebrow">Repository Highlights</span>
			<h2>The site points directly at the real capabilities already present in the repo.</h2>
			<p>
				This avoids fake product copy. The landing narrative is tied to features that exist today:
				type checking, native packages, example programs, benchmark scripts, and editor tooling.
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="example-grid">
			<article class="docs-card">
				<h3>Examples and demos</h3>
				<p>
					Explore manual examples under <code>examples/</code>, including visible window demos and a
					playable Flappy Bird clone powered by the official <code>window</code> package.
				</p>
			</article>
			<article class="docs-card">
				<h3>Package story</h3>
				<p>
					Mog supports package manifests, lockfiles, native package APIs, and resolution through
					<code>@import(...)</code> for both modules and native packages.
				</p>
			</article>
		</div>
		<div class="cta-banner">
			<div>
				<span class="eyebrow">Start Here</span>
				<h2>Read the docs, then tune the voice.</h2>
				<p>
					The structure is now in place for a polished public site. Next iterations can deepen the
					reference, add versioned docs, and refine the brand voice without reworking the stack.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="hero-actions">
				<a class="primary" href="/docs/">Open Docs</a>
				<a class="secondary" href="/manifesto/">Read the Manifesto</a>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>
</MarketingLayout>
